  "prompt": "How do I learn probability in a day?",
  "response": "Learning probability in a single day is a challenging task, but it can be manageable if you focus on the fundamentals, streamline your study approach, and practice actively. Here's a step-by-step plan to help you make the most of your day:\n\n---\n\n### **1. Start with the Basics (1\u20132 hours)**\n- **Understand Key Concepts**:\n  - Probability: The likelihood of an event occurring (expressed as a number between 0 and 1).\n  - Sample Space: All possible outcomes of an experiment.\n  - Event: A subset of the sample space.\n  - Independent vs. Dependent Events: Events that do or do not influence each other.\n- **Learn Probability Rules**:\n  - Addition Rule: P(A or B) = P(A) + P(B) \u2013 P(A and B).\n  - Multiplication Rule: P(A and B) = P(A) \u00d7 P(B|A) (for dependent events).\n  - Complementary Rule: P(not A) = 1 \u2013 P(A).\n\n---\n\n### **2. Study Common Probability Distributions (2\u20133 hours)**\n- **Discrete Distributions**:\n  - Binomial Distribution: Probability of a specific number of successes in a fixed number of trials.\n  - Poisson",
